      Expenses
   =20
 =20

Mohamed Ali Rashid used to be a partner at Apollo Global Management Inc., t=
he big private equity firm. As part of his job, he would fly around to visi=
t=C2=A0companies in which he had made, or was considering making, investmen=
ts on behalf of the private equity funds that Apollo manages. He spent a lo=
t of money on flights, hotels and meals as he evaluated investments and mon=
itored portfolio companies. Naturally he put all of these expenses on his A=
pollo corporate credit card. That=E2=80=99s why he had the card. He=C2=A0di=
dn=E2=80=99t pay for his flights to monitor portfolio companies.
Neither, to be clear, did Apollo.=C2=A0Apollo, his firm, turned around and =
billed those expenses to the funds that it managed for investors=C2=A0or to=
 the portfolio companies that it ran for those funds.=C2=A0Its limited part=
nership agreements with those funds said that the funds would pay for Apoll=
o=E2=80=99s expenses =E2=80=9Carising in connection with [the fund=E2=80=99=
s] operations and the acquisition, ownership, and maintenance of investment=
s in Portfolio Companies.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0And Rashid =E2=80=94=C2=A0or his assistant =E2=80=94=C2=A0had to fill=
 out expense reports explaining each expense that he charged on his corpora=
te card, and=C2=A0allocating=C2=A0each expense to a particular investment, =
so that Apollo could bill the expense to the right funds or companies.
  [2]

So far this is totally normal, just the standard operating procedure for pr=
ivate equity firms. Less normally, Rashid also put hundreds of thousands of=
 dollars of personal expenses on his corporate card, whoops. =E2=80=9CDurin=
g 2010, Rashid regularly charged expenses related to personal grooming serv=
ices that he received at a high-end hair salon to his Apollo corporate cred=
it card,=E2=80=9D the US Securities and Exchange Commission said=C2=A0when =
it sued him for fraud in 2017. On his expense reports, he described these h=
aircuts as=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmeals with management=E2=80=9D of portfolio compan=
ies, but his assistant noticed that =E2=80=9Cthere was no restaurant in New=
 York with the name of the vendor on the credit card statement, but that a =
New York hair salon had that name.=E2=80=9D She reported her suspicions to =
Apollo=E2=80=99s chief financial officer, who investigated and found other =
fake expenses; later a law firm investigation found even more fake expenses=
. Ultimately Rashid left and agreed to pay Apollo back $325,000 for these f=
ake personal expenses.
And the SEC sued, because this is pretty obviously fraud. But what=C2=A0kin=
d=C2=A0of fraud? The SEC sued Rashid for defrauding Apollo=E2=80=99s=C2=A0p=
rivate equity funds, which ultimately paid the fake expenses.
  [3]
=C2=A0Apollo, the company, gave Rashid the credit card, but ultimately it b=
illed his expenses to its clients, so the clients were the ones who were de=
frauded. And Rashid, as a senior partner at Apollo, was an adviser and a fi=
duciary for those funds, so the law prohibited him from defrauding them.
At trial, Rashid offered a clever defense: Yes, obviously, he was doing fra=
ud. But he wasn=E2=80=99t doing fraud=C2=A0on the funds, because he didn=E2=
=80=99t know that his expenses would be billed to the funds. He just knew t=
hat Apollo gave him a credit card and paid the bill. As far as he knew, he =
was just defrauding Apollo, his employer, not the funds for which he was a =
fiduciary. =E2=80=9CRashid testified that he had believed that the expenses=
 for which he sought reimbursement were paid by the Apollo-affiliated manag=
ement companies, not the funds.=E2=80=9D
  [4]

This defense did not work at trial. The judge did not believe him, finding =
=E2=80=9Cthat his testimony was =E2=80=98an after-the-fact construct to avo=
id liability.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It does not sound especially plausible=
 to me either. He had to submit expense reports that=C2=A0allocated=C2=A0ea=
ch expense=C2=A0to some particular Apollo investment. The point of doing th=
at was=C2=A0obviously=C2=A0so that Apollo could bill the expenses to the fu=
nds that made those investments.=C2=A0The judge concluded that at best he w=
as at least =E2=80=9Crecklessly indifferent,=E2=80=9D and so liable for fra=
ud.
Rashid appealed, and yesterday he won.=C2=A0Here is a bizarre opinion from =
the US Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit finding that actually no pri=
vate equity professional had any reason to think that his travel expenses w=
ould be billed to a fund, so Rashid couldn=E2=80=99t have been doing fraud =
on his funds:
We recognize that Rashid committed serious, and almost certainly criminal, =
misdeeds by improperly seeking reimbursement for personal expenses. But we =
must not confuse the fraud Rashid committed against his employer with fraud=
 committed against the funds.=C2=A0
Okay. I mean, on the one hand, that feels like an absurd technicality; on t=
he other hand, I love absurd technicalities and have no problem with this i=
n theory. Here, though, I don=E2=80=99t know:
Apollo maintained written reimbursement policies that outlined which expens=
es could and could not be reimbursed. The policies generally stated that =
=E2=80=9CApollo [would] reimburse employees for business and travel expense=
s incurred while performing their duties, provided the expenses [were] nece=
ssary, reasonable and appropriately documented.=E2=80=9D The guidance given=
 to Apollo employees, however, did not explain who ultimately paid for reim=
bursements.
I guess? I don=E2=80=99t buy it, but whatever.=C2=A0But then things take a =
wild=C2=A0turn:
During the relevant time, Apollo=E2=80=99s accounts receivable department i=
mproperly charged all expenses relating to the monitoring of a fund=E2=80=
=99s portfolio company directly to the fund, in contravention of the fund p=
artnership agreements requiring that the fund-specific Apollo management co=
mpanies bear the cost of such =E2=80=9Cadministrative expenses.=E2=80=9D
What.
The record shows that many Apollo professionals =E2=80=94 including Apollo=
=E2=80=99s current and former CFOs and an employee who held the same title =
as Rashid=E2=80=94believed that Apollo, and not the funds, would pay for ex=
penses incurred while monitoring the funds. =E2=80=A6 In fact, it would hav=
e been difficult for any of them to have discovered the truth: that Apollo=
=E2=80=99s accounts receivable department was improperly billing the funds =
for expenses that should have been allocated to the Apollo-affiliated manag=
ement companies. And if Rashid had decided to look into the matter further,=
 he would have reasonably consulted the fund partnership agreements and rea=
ched the same conclusion as his peers: that the Apollo-affiliated managemen=
t companies were supposed to pay for his claimed expenses.
What? Here, on appeal in a garden-variety six-figure SEC fraud case, the co=
urt just casually accused Apollo of a much bigger fraud, =E2=80=9Cimproperl=
y billing=E2=80=9D all of its expenses to its funds, when it was supposed t=
o pay them itself.=C2=A0That =E2=80=A6=C2=A0seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wrong?=C2=
=A0The court quotes a provision of one fund=E2=80=99s limited partnership a=
greement saying that =E2=80=9Cthe Apollo-affiliated management company asso=
ciated with that specific fund was responsible for =E2=80=98[a]dministrativ=
e [e]xpenses,=E2=80=99=C2=A0including =E2=80=98all costs and expenses . . .=
 incurred in developing, negotiating and structuring Portfolio Investments=
=E2=80=99=C2=A0and =E2=80=98all ordinary costs and expenses . . . incurred =
in monitoring Portfolio Investments,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D but I suspect the co=
urt is misreading something.=C2=A0Surely the agreements said that the funds=
 would reimburse Apollo for its travel expenses in making investments and m=
onitoring portfolio companies.=C2=A0
You can tell in part because the SEC said so in its case against Rashid, qu=
oting the limited partnership agreements. You can tell because billing at l=
east some travel and meal expenses to the fund is standard practice in priv=
ate equity.
  [5]
 But you can also tell because=C2=A0nobody has sued Apollo for this suppose=
d huge fraud.=C2=A0Rashid improperly billed about $325,000 of fake expenses=
 to Apollo=E2=80=99s clients. For this, the SEC sued him. It also settled w=
ith=C2=A0Apollo, for failure to supervise him. But the appeals court here i=
s saying that Apollo =E2=80=9Cimproperly=E2=80=9D billed=C2=A0all=C2=A0of i=
ts partners=E2=80=99=C2=A0real=C2=A0travel expenses to its funds for years.=
 If that were true =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t th=
e SEC have sued it for=C2=A0that?=C2=A0Surely all=C2=A0of Apollo=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0actual=C2=A0travel expenses were several orders of magnitude greater =
than=C2=A0one partner=E2=80=99s fake=C2=A0travel expenses. Why go after $32=
5,000 of improperly billed fake expenses when there are many millions of do=
llars of improperly billed real expenses? Doesn=E2=80=99t seem right.

