      Nigeria vs. crypto
   =20
 =20

Probably the strongest case for crypto is that cryptocurrencies meet a real=
 need for people who live in countries with unstable currencies and weak fi=
nancial and legal institutions. If keeping your money in the local bank mea=
ns that your money might lose all its value because of inflation, or be sei=
zed by the government, then you will want to keep your money somewhere else=
. Keeping it on the blockchain =E2=80=94=C2=A0in Bitcoin, in other cryptocu=
rrencies, or in stablecoins pegged to the US dollar =E2=80=94=C2=A0arguably=
 solves both your problems. The government probably=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t take=
 your money if it=E2=80=99s on the blockchain, and it can=E2=80=99t inflate=
 away the value of your money if it=E2=80=99s in Bitcoin or dollars. There =
are other ways to store your money that are stable and hard to find =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0diamonds, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but crypto is probably easier to hid=
e, transfer, sell and spend than most of them.
On the other hand, there=C2=A0is no particular reason for your government t=
o like this. For one thing, it is rude to the government to say =E2=80=9Cth=
e institutions and currency here are bad so I=E2=80=99m putting my money in=
 Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D For another thing, if the government=C2=A0wants=C2=A0to =
seize your money or whatever, it will be annoyed if you make that difficult=
: You may see =E2=80=9Cweak financial and legal institutions,=E2=80=9D but =
the government sees =E2=80=9Clegitimate enforcement of our laws against imp=
roper currency transactions.=E2=80=9D Also, though, if everyone decides to =
get out of the local banks and into Bitcoin, that is going to=C2=A0create=
=C2=A0problems; it will drive down the local currency and make the banks we=
aker.
The crypto maximalist reply is probably =E2=80=9Ctough luck, government, th=
ere=E2=80=99s nothing you can do about it, code is law, the blockchain is a=
 technology that overthrows censorship.=E2=80=9D There are two main problem=
s with that reply:
=09The =E2=80=9C$5 wrench attack=E2=80=9D: If your money is stored in a sec=
ure, decentralized, censorship-resistant cryptographic blockchain, that=E2=
=80=99s super, and the government probably can=E2=80=99t just seize it by p=
ressing a button, but the government probably=C2=A0can=C2=A0throw you in ja=
il until you cough up your password.=09On-ramps and off-ramps: Turning your=
 local currency into crypto, and turning crypto back into spendable money,=
=C2=A0probably=C2=A0involves going through a crypto=C2=A0exchange. A crypto=
 exchange is=C2=A0probably=C2=A0a big centralized company with a corporate =
charter, a money-transmitting license, banking relationships=C2=A0and human=
 executives. It has some surface area that is vulnerable to government pres=
sure, and if the government doesn=E2=80=99t like all its citizens getting i=
nto crypto, it will probably put some pressure on the exchanges.

If you want, I guess you could apply what I just said, in some loose metaph=
orical sense, to, say, the relationship between the US=C2=A0government and=
=C2=A0Binance. But there are more direct applications. The Wall Street Jour=
nal=C2=A0reported Tuesday:

Tigran Gambaryan, Binance=E2=80=99s head of financial-crime compliance, fle=
w to Nigeria=E2=80=99s capital to solve a problem: The government had blame=
d the world=E2=80=99s largest crypto exchange for crashing the currency. ..=
.
Nigerian authorities detained Gambaryan and a colleague, Nadeem Anjarwalla,=
 a U.K. and Kenyan national and Binance=E2=80=99s regional manager for Afri=
ca, according to the men=E2=80=99s families.
The Binance employees, who are being held in a guarded house, haven=E2=80=
=99t been charged with any crimes. The government, which invited them to Ni=
geria for meetings, hasn=E2=80=99t publicly discussed the detentions. =E2=
=80=A6
Because the government rationed who could exchange the local currency for t=
he dollar and at what exchange rate, many sought refuge in digital currenci=
es pegged to the U.S. dollar, known as stablecoins.=C2=A0
The stablecoin trade in essence became a black market, displaying an unoffi=
cial exchange rate between the local currency, the naira, and the dollar th=
at was much weaker than the government=E2=80=99s rates. Binance, the most p=
opular exchange, became the go-to place to check that black-market rate, ac=
cording to currency traders.=C2=A0
Bayo Onanuga, a special adviser to the Nigerian president, accused Binance =
of setting the exchange rate for Nigeria and hijacking the role of the cent=
ral bank.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CCrypto should be banned in our country or else this bleeding of ou=
r currency will continue unabated,=E2=80=9D he wrote in a post on X.

The Financial Times adds:

Nigeria is pressing Binance for information on its top 100 users in the cou=
ntry, as well as all transaction history for the past six months, as its de=
tention of two senior executives at the cryptocurrency exchange enters a th=
ird week.
The request is at the centre of negotiations between Binance and Nigeria, w=
hich sees the company as a crucial link undermining government efforts to s=
tabilise its currency, the naira. The period under review is crucial becaus=
e it tallies with the timeline of Nigeria=E2=80=99s devaluation of its curr=
ency.

In some broad philosophical sense, the appeal of crypto is that the governm=
ent can=E2=80=99t just ask a bank for your account information and then sei=
ze your account. But in a practical sense that=E2=80=99s not always entirel=
y=C2=A0true.

