<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Expenses</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mohamed Ali Rashid used to be a partner at Apo=
llo Global Management Inc., the big private equity firm. As part of his job=
, he would fly around to visit=C2=A0companies in which he had made, or was =
considering making, investments on behalf of the private equity funds that =
Apollo manages. He spent a lot of money on flights, hotels and meals as he =
evaluated investments and monitored portfolio companies. Naturally he put a=
ll of these expenses on his Apollo corporate credit card. That=E2=80=99s wh=
y he had the card. <em>He=C2=A0</em>didn=E2=80=99t pay for his flights to m=
onitor portfolio companies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Neither, to be clear, did Apollo.=C2=A0Apollo,=
 his firm, turned around and billed those expenses to the funds that it man=
aged for investors=C2=A0or to the portfolio companies that it ran for those=
 funds.=C2=A0Its limited partnership agreements with those funds said that =
the funds would pay for Apollo=E2=80=99s expenses =E2=80=9Carising in conne=
ction with [the fund=E2=80=99s] operations and the acquisition, ownership, =
and maintenance of investments in Portfolio Companies.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And Rashid =E2=80=94=C2=A0or his assistant =E2=80=94=C2=A0had to =
fill out expense reports explaining each expense that he charged on his cor=
porate card, and=C2=A0<em>allocating=C2=A0</em>each expense to a particular=
 investment, so that Apollo could bill the expense to the right funds or co=
mpanies.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So far this is totally normal, just the standa=
rd operating procedure for private equity firms. Less normally, Rashid also=
 put hundreds of thousands of dollars of personal expenses on his corporate=
 card, whoops. =E2=80=9CDuring 2010, Rashid regularly charged expenses rela=
ted to personal grooming services that he received at a high-end hair salon=
 to his Apollo corporate credit card,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34684872.258367/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maW=
xlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAxOC9jb21wMjQwOTMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB7d5a4721" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">the US Securities and Exchange Commission said</=
a>=C2=A0when it sued him for fraud in 2017. On his expense reports, he desc=
ribed these haircuts as=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmeals with management=E2=80=9D of por=
tfolio companies, but his assistant noticed that =E2=80=9Cthere was no rest=
aurant in New York with the name of the vendor on the credit card statement=
, but that a New York hair salon had that name.=E2=80=9D She reported her s=
uspicions to Apollo=E2=80=99s chief financial officer, who investigated and=
 found other fake expenses; later a law firm investigation found even more =
fake expenses. Ultimately Rashid left and agreed to pay Apollo back $325,00=
0 for these fake personal expenses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the SEC sued, because this is pretty obvio=
usly fraud. But what=C2=A0<em>kind=C2=A0</em>of fraud? The SEC sued Rashid =
for defrauding Apollo=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>private equity funds</em>, which u=
ltimately paid the fake expenses.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Apollo, the company, gave Rashid the credit card, but ultimately =
it billed his expenses to its clients, so the clients were the ones who wer=
e defrauded. And Rashid, as a senior partner at Apollo, was an adviser and =
a fiduciary for those funds, so the law <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/34684872.258367/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L=
3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1LzgwYi02/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB319cc8c7" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">proh=
ibited him from defrauding them</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At trial, Rashid offered a clever defense: Yes=
, obviously, he was doing fraud. But he wasn=E2=80=99t doing fraud=C2=A0<em=
>on the funds</em>, because he didn=E2=80=99t <em>know</em> that his expens=
es would be billed to the funds. He just knew that Apollo gave him a credit=
 card and paid the bill. As far as he knew, he was just defrauding Apollo, =
his employer, not the funds for which he was a fiduciary. =E2=80=9CRashid t=
estified that he had believed that the expenses for which he sought reimbur=
sement were paid by the Apollo-affiliated management companies, not the fun=
ds.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This defense did not work at trial. The judge =
did not believe him, finding =E2=80=9Cthat his testimony was =E2=80=98an af=
ter-the-fact construct to avoid liability.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It does n=
ot sound especially plausible to me either. He had to submit expense report=
s that=C2=A0allocated=C2=A0each expense=C2=A0to some particular Apollo inve=
stment. The point of doing that was=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=A0</em>so that Ap=
ollo could bill the expenses to the funds that made those investments.=C2=
=A0The judge concluded that at best he was at least =E2=80=9Crecklessly ind=
ifferent,=E2=80=9D and so liable for fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rashid appealed, and yesterday <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34684872.258367/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMTMvZXgtYXBvbGxvLXBhcnRuZXIt=
Z2V0cy1zZWMtZnJhdWQtanVkZ21lbnQtdGhyb3duLW91dC1vbi1hcHBlYWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDM=
xNDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bbc447e2d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">he won</a>.=C2=A0Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34684872.258367/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9=
kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JMT2ZnUU9hQjBGay92MA/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBfb87f6db" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">bizarre opinion</a> from the US Court of Appe=
als for the Second Circuit finding that actually no private equity professi=
onal had any reason to think that his travel expenses would be billed to a =
fund, so Rashid couldn=E2=80=99t have been doing fraud on his funds:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We recognize that Rashid committed=
 serious, and almost certainly criminal, misdeeds by improperly seeking rei=
mbursement for personal expenses. But we must not confuse the fraud Rashid =
committed against his employer with fraud committed against the funds.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay. I mean, on the one hand, that feels like=
 an absurd technicality; on the other hand, I love absurd technicalities an=
d have no problem with this in theory. Here, though, I don=E2=80=99t know:<=
/p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apollo maintained written reimburs=
ement policies that outlined which expenses could and could not be reimburs=
ed. The policies generally stated that =E2=80=9CApollo [would] reimburse em=
ployees for business and travel expenses incurred while performing their du=
ties, provided the expenses [were] necessary, reasonable and appropriately =
documented.=E2=80=9D The guidance given to Apollo employees, however, did n=
ot explain who ultimately paid for reimbursements.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess? I don=E2=80=99t buy it, but whatever.=
=C2=A0But then things take a wild=C2=A0turn:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the relevant time, Apollo=
=E2=80=99s accounts receivable department improperly charged all expenses r=
elating to the monitoring of a fund=E2=80=99s portfolio company directly to=
 the fund, in contravention of the fund partnership agreements requiring th=
at the fund-specific Apollo management companies bear the cost of such =E2=
=80=9Cadministrative expenses.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What.</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The record shows that many Apollo =
professionals =E2=80=94 including Apollo=E2=80=99s current and former CFOs =
and an employee who held the same title as Rashid=E2=80=94believed that Apo=
llo, and not the funds, would pay for expenses incurred while monitoring th=
e funds. =E2=80=A6 In fact, it would have been difficult for any of them to=
 have discovered the truth: that Apollo=E2=80=99s accounts receivable depar=
tment was improperly billing the funds for expenses that should have been a=
llocated to the Apollo-affiliated management companies. And if Rashid had d=
ecided to look into the matter further, he would have reasonably consulted =
the fund partnership agreements and reached the same conclusion as his peer=
s: that the Apollo-affiliated management companies were supposed to pay for=
 his claimed expenses.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? Here, on appeal in a garden-variety six-=
figure SEC fraud case, the court just casually accused Apollo of a much big=
ger fraud, =E2=80=9Cimproperly billing=E2=80=9D all of its expenses to its =
funds, when it was supposed to pay them itself.=C2=A0That =E2=80=A6=C2=A0se=
ems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wrong?=C2=A0The court quotes a provision of one fund=E2=
=80=99s limited partnership agreement saying that =E2=80=9Cthe Apollo-affil=
iated management company associated with that specific fund was responsible=
 for =E2=80=98[a]dministrative [e]xpenses,=E2=80=99=C2=A0including =E2=80=
=98all costs and expenses . . . incurred in developing, negotiating and str=
ucturing Portfolio Investments=E2=80=99=C2=A0and =E2=80=98all ordinary cost=
s and expenses . . . incurred in monitoring Portfolio Investments,=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D but I suspect the court is misreading something.=C2=A0Surely the =
agreements said that the funds would reimburse Apollo for its travel expens=
es in making investments and monitoring portfolio companies.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can tell in part because the SEC said so i=
n its case against Rashid, quoting the limited partnership agreements. You =
can tell because billing at least some travel and meal expenses to the fund=
 is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34684872.25836=
7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90cmF2ZWwtZXhwZW5zZXMtZW50ZXItbHBzL=
XJhZGFyLXNjcmVlbnMtMTQ2NzcyNzEzNg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7414741f" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">standard practice</a> in private equity.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> But you can also tell because=C2=A0<em>nobody has sued Apollo for this=
 supposed huge fraud</em>.=C2=A0Rashid improperly billed about $325,000 of =
fake expenses to Apollo=E2=80=99s clients. For this, the SEC sued him. It a=
lso <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34684872.25836=
7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAxNi0xNjU/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB39adadb5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">settled with=C2=A0<em>Apollo</em></a>, fo=
r failure to supervise him. But the appeals court here is saying that Apoll=
o =E2=80=9Cimproperly=E2=80=9D billed=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of its partner=
s=E2=80=99=C2=A0<em>real=C2=A0</em>travel expenses to its funds for years. =
If that were true =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t the=
 SEC have sued it for=C2=A0<em>that?=C2=A0</em>Surely <em>all=C2=A0</em>of =
Apollo=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>travel expenses were several ord=
ers of magnitude greater than=C2=A0<em>one </em>partner=E2=80=99s <em>fake=
=C2=A0</em>travel expenses. Why go after $325,000 of improperly billed fake=
 expenses when there are many millions of dollars of improperly billed real=
 expenses? Doesn=E2=80=99t seem right.</p>
