<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Probably the strongest case for crypto is that=
 cryptocurrencies meet a real need for people who live in countries with un=
stable currencies and weak financial and legal institutions. If keeping you=
r money in the local bank means that your money might lose all its value be=
cause of inflation, or be seized by the government, then you will want to k=
eep your money somewhere else. Keeping it on the blockchain =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
in Bitcoin, in other cryptocurrencies, or in stablecoins pegged to the US d=
ollar =E2=80=94=C2=A0arguably solves both your problems. The government pro=
bably=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t take your money if it=E2=80=99s on the blockchain,=
 and it can=E2=80=99t inflate away the value of your money if it=E2=80=99s =
in Bitcoin or dollars. There are other ways to store your money that are st=
able and hard to find =E2=80=94=C2=A0diamonds, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but cryp=
to is probably easier to hide, transfer, sell and spend than most of them.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, there=C2=A0is no particular=
 reason for your government to like this. For one thing, it is rude to the =
government to say =E2=80=9Cthe institutions and currency here are bad so I=
=E2=80=99m putting my money in Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D For another thing, if the =
government=C2=A0<em>wants=C2=A0</em>to seize your money or whatever, it wil=
l be annoyed if you make that difficult: You may see =E2=80=9Cweak financia=
l and legal institutions,=E2=80=9D but the government sees =E2=80=9Clegitim=
ate enforcement of our laws against improper currency transactions.=E2=80=
=9D Also, though, if <em>everyone</em> decides to get out of the local bank=
s and into Bitcoin, that is going to=C2=A0<em>create=C2=A0</em>problems; it=
 will drive down the local currency and make the banks weaker.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The crypto maximalist reply is probably =E2=80=
=9Ctough luck, government, there=E2=80=99s nothing you can do about it, cod=
e is law, the blockchain is a technology that overthrows censorship.=E2=80=
=9D There are two main problems with that reply:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34684872.258367/aHR0cHM6Ly94a2NkLmNvbS81Mz=
gv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB88bb5050" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">$5 wrench attack</a>=E2=80=9D=
: If your money is stored in a secure, decentralized, censorship-resistant =
cryptographic blockchain, that=E2=80=99s super, and the government probably=
 can=E2=80=99t just seize it by pressing a button, but the government proba=
bly=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>throw you in jail until you cough up your passwo=
rd.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">On-ramps and off-ramps: Turnin=
g your local currency into crypto, and turning crypto back into spendable m=
oney,=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>involves going through a crypto=C2=A0<em>=
exchange</em>. A crypto exchange is=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>a big centr=
alized company with a corporate charter, a money-transmitting license, bank=
ing relationships=C2=A0and human executives. It has some surface area that =
is vulnerable to government pressure, and if the government doesn=E2=80=99t=
 like all its citizens getting into crypto, it will probably put some press=
ure on the exchanges.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want, I guess you could apply what I ju=
st said, in some loose metaphorical sense, to, say, the <a href=3D"https://=
